Using Both Together in Postman

URL (with path parameters):

https://api.example.com/users/:userId/posts/:postId

Params tab:

Key	Value
userId	101
postId	2001
sort	desc
limit	5

Final URL sent by Postman:

https://api.example.com/users/101/posts/2001?sort=desc&limit=5

‚úÖ Postman automatically replaces path params and appends query params.

What is Shadow DOM?

Shadow DOM is part of Web Components

It allows a self-contained DOM tree inside an element

Normal Selenium locators cannot see inside shadow DOM

Selenium 4 supports nested shadow DOM by chaining getShadowRoot()

üîπ 3Ô∏è‚É£ Nested Shadow DOM

Some elements have shadow inside shadow:

<custom-element id="host1">
  #shadow-root
      <custom-inner id="inner">
          #shadow-root
              <input id="nestedInput">
      </custom-inner>
</custom-element>

You can handle it like this:

WebElement host1 = driver.findElement(By.cssSelector("custom-element#host1"));
WebElement shadowRoot1 = host1.getShadowRoot();

WebElement innerHost = shadowRoot1.findElement(By.cssSelector("custom-inner#inner"));
WebElement shadowRoot2 = innerHost.getShadowRoot();

WebElement nestedInput = shadowRoot2.findElement(By.cssSelector("input#nestedInput"));
nestedInput.sendKeys("Hello");

Chain getShadowRoot() for each nested shadow host

üîπ 4Ô∏è‚É£ Tips for Beginners

Always locate the shadow host first (<custom-element> or similar)

Then call .getShadowRoot()

Use CSS selectors inside shadow root

For nested shadow DOM, repeat the process

Method 4: Get Coordinates Programmatically in Java (Optional)

If you have a WebElement in Selenium:

WebElement element = driver.findElement(By.id("submit"));

// Get element location in viewport
Point location = element.getLocation();
int x = location.getX();
int y = location.getY();
System.out.println("Element location: " + x + ", " + y);

